on community legal education, community mobilization, advocacy, and dialogue with police and legislators about law enforcement issues and law reform. Community- based organizations of MSM, transgender people, sex workers, and people who use drugs are educating their communities about the law and advocating their governments for law reform and improvements to law enforcement practices. ii A Community Legal Service has been established to provide legal assistance to entertainment workers/ sex workers in Phnom Penh, Cambodia.127 iii LBH Masyarakat (Community Legal Aid Institute) is an NGO that provides legal education and assistance to key populations in Jakarta, Indonesia.128 iv The Equal Project in Myanmar provides HIV-related legal assistance to key populations in partnership with community-based networks of key populations in Yangon.129 v The Empower Foundation in Thailand advocates for labour protection measures to be extended to sex work as a legitimate occupation and protection of sex workers from police harassment or abuse.130 Capacity building of police i Cambodia The Police Community Partnership Initiative (PCPI) of the Ministry of Interior of Cambodia and FHI 360 (an international non-profit health organization) works through teams comprised of community representatives, local authorities, law enforcement officials, health workers, paralegal workers, and local NGOs to ensure an enabling environment for HIV-prevention, treatment, care, and support services for entertainment workers, MSM, transgender people, and people who use drugs. PCPI creates partnerships through capacity building and facilitates dialogue during coordination meetings at the community level. Sensitization workshops and trainings for police are co-facilitated by government and FHI 360. Police conduct coordination meetings every two months at the post level and quarterly meetings at the sub-district and municipal levels to address barriers to HIV efforts. 127 UNAIDS (2013), National HIV Legal Review Report (unpub. draft). 128 International Development Law Organization (2010), Stakeholder report: Rapid needs assessment of the legal needs of people living with HIV and key populations in Jakarta, Rome: IDLO. 129 UNAIDS (2014), National HIV Legal Review Report (in print). 130 UNDP (2013), Sex work and the law in Asia and the Pacific, Bangkok: UNDP, p. 5. 54 HIV AND THE LAW IN SOUTH-EAST ASIA CHAPTEr 8: CONCLUSIONS In the HIV \u2018hot spot\u2019 areas where PCPI is implemented, police are directed not to arrest people for possession of small quantities of drugs for their personal use. Law enforcement efforts are focused on drug sale and supply, rather than possession of small personal quantities. There is some evidence that PCPI has improved police attitudes towards key populations.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "da3f9789-4640-410c-84c3-7702ec64569f": {"__data__": {"id_": "da3f9789-4640-410c-84c3-7702ec64569f", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-law-south-east-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV and the Law in South-East Asia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-law-south-east-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "01219d31b1c410372a0a3c6c855c05adf4fffe8f0c3797bf39995cd4888af08b"}, "2": {"node_id": "15463e1b-9dbb-477e-96bb-cc6a8f67cd74", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-law-south-east-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "8dc4105d8c37fdc8080f18ca1472093da98515405a23e12c69c771982921e4a1"}}, "hash": "970ce66196c2f94b6a02bf8907de124e3bb58ba7362c7731383f0b69a99b2301", "text": "There is some evidence that PCPI has improved police attitudes towards key populations. Findings from pilot sites indicate that PCPI has reduced fear of police among most-at-risk populations.131 There has been an increase in the utilization of services, better communication between the police and community partners, and confidence among entertainment establishment owners to cooperate with NGO partners in providing condoms.132 ii Thailand The Royal Thai Police, Ministry of Justice, Ministry of Public Health, Foundation for AIDS Rights, and UNDP are supporting a police training programme to address HIV-related discrimination in Thailand.133 The programme aims to sensitize law enforcement officers to issues concerning human rights and to provide general knowledge on HIV, such as modes of transmission and HIV prevention. The programme builds upon an initiative to educate junior police cadets that started in 2012. Higher-level police officers are also being targeted to ensure sustainable integration of HIV and related human rights issues into the police training curriculum.134 To date, 40 police have been trained to provide training to junior police cadets, and focus group discussions were held with 60 commissioned police officers from multiple levels to inform the learning programme for senior police officers. The training package includes: \u2022 Basic knowledge of HIV (e.g., epidemic overview, modes of transmission, voluntary counselling and", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "3cd3698a-5863-4025-91d0-e3837b4dab82": {"__data__": {"id_": "3cd3698a-5863-4025-91d0-e3837b4dab82", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-law-south-east-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV and the Law in South-East Asia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-law-south-east-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "24f083754009a591762ad4f738338f003f04b6ae81760643f2fcf5e1b9401cc5"}, "3": {"node_id": "81fa26a0-6057-47ca-b03e-dc2266f45ca8", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-law-south-east-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "8372228a77081c04f458134e875d3e6fcfd8c9c2fbb7b76d78da4b0191aaa25a"}}, "hash": "eaecfd27a4a38372b8bc6d46d575cd9b48d6dbdfb94448b0f8ec0bba50459fa7", "text": "treatment, prevention, key affected populations, etc.); \u2022 Guidelines for police practices, HIV policy and management in the workplace, police practice, and the implementation of HIV prevention; \u2022 Training toolkits. Also in Thailand, the community-based sex worker organization SWING implements a police cadet internship programme and cadet training curriculum to educate new recruits about sex workers\u2019 health rights and expose police cadets to peer-based HIV prevention activities.135 131 See Thomson, N. et al. (2012), The village/commune safety policy and HIV prevention efforts among key affected populations in Cambodia: Finding balance, Harm Reduction Journal, 9:31. 132 UNAIDS/UNDP submission to UN Community of Practice, July 2013. 133 The programme is known as the \u201cThai Police as Key Cha