V/AIDS. 5.4 Recommendations for women Migrant workers Associations/Organizations/Unions: Women migrant workers associations/organizations/unions that can leverage their first-hand knowledge of target communities are best poised to advance the issues of safe migration and the reduction of HIV vulnerability. l Incorporate the findings of this research into their advocacy and outreach programs. l Strengthen links and network with their counterparts in other origin and host countries, especially those that have an international membership. 5.5 Research and Monitoring Finally, gender-sensitive information and data on labour migration, epidemiology, and social health - especially in relation to the socio-economic impacts of HIV vulnerability and infection - need to be strengthened via the efforts of all the stakeholders identified above as a way of building evidence-based approaches to policy formulation and programme design. ReGIONAL ANALYSIS 61 1. About JUNIMA. Available at: http://www.hivmobilitysea.org/ 2. Aday, Lu Ann. 1994. Health status of vulnerable populations. Annual Review of Public Health. 15:487-509 3. Agarwal B. 1997. Bargaining and gender relations: with and beyond the household. FCND Discussion Paper 27. International Food Policy Research Institute 4. Ahmed A S. 2007. Post-traumatic stress disorder, resilience and vulnerability. Advances in Psychiatric Treatment (2007), vol. 13, 369\u2013375 doi: 10.1192/apt.bp.106.003236 5. Arif G M. 1998. Reintegration of Pakistani Return Migrants from the Middle east in the Domestic Labour Market. The Pakistan Development Review. 37 : 2 (Summer 1998) pp. 99-124 6. Arab League. 2008. The Relationship between the League of Arab States and Different Regional Groupings. A Meeting with Foreign Ambassadors at the League of Arab States 21-1-2008. Available at: www.arableagueonline.org/las/ picture_gallery/thearab%20economic11r.pdf. 7. Asia Pacific Council of AIDS service Organizations (APCASO). 2007. Prevention counseling for 