ng with or affected by HIV throughout the region. The Socio-economic Impact of HIV on Women and Girls 3 Contributors The HIV-APCoP received responses from: Adji Danya Delita Hakim, Head, Poverty Reduction and MDG Unit, UNDP Indonesia Annie McPherson, Igat HOPE, Papua New Guinea Aradhana Johri, Additional Secretary, National AIDS Control Office, Government of India Atif Khurshid, Research Analyst, with Susana T. Fried, Senior Policy Adviser, Brian Lutz, Policy Specialist, UNDP Carol Flore-Smerecziak, Deputy Resident Representative, UNDP Papua New Guinea Dr. Nabeel M. K., National Programme Officer, UNAIDS India, and Moderator of Solution Exchange AIDS Community G. Pramod Kumar, Senior Programme Advisor, HIV, Health and Development, UNDP Asia-Pacific Regional Centre Jacob Kupu, Program Officer-HIV/AIDS, Department of National Planning and Monitoring, WAIGANI Lisa Williams, Papua New Guinea Maura Elaripe, HIV Health Project Coordinator, Igat Hope Inc., Papua New Guinea Narmada Acharya, Social Mobilization and Partnerships Adviser, UNAIDS Cambodia Pauline Kenna, Gender Advisor, and Jo Kaybryn, Gender and HIV TA, Timgim Laip, Papua New Guinea Peterson Magoola, HIV Programme Specialist, UNDP Papua New Guinea Philip Castro, Programme Officer for HIV and AIDS, UNDP Philippines Silja Anniina Rajander, Consultant, Cambodian Community of Women Living with HIV/AIDS Stella-Marie Kombul, Program Officer- Youth, HIV and AIDS, ChildFund Papua New Guinea Svetlana Negroustoueva, MEASURE Evaluation Swairee Rupasinghe, UNDP Sri Lanka www.hivapcop.org 4 Survey Prior to the e-discussion, an online survey was conducted amongst members of the Asia Pacific Community of Practice on HIV, Gender and Human Rights (HIV- APCoP). Members, who were informed of the findings of the regional analysis on the socio-economic impact of HIV on women and girls in Asia, were asked to identify the most critical impacts of HIV on women and girls in the region across a range of issues. Respondents rated the issues (see list below) on a scale of 1-5 (with 1 being the least important and 5 the most important) and also provided specific examples of initiatives implemented by government, civil society and the private sector. Economic: Income; Assets (e.g. ownership of property); Credit, Debt, Employment, Other Food and Nutrition: Accessibility; Affordability; Quality; Other Education: School attendance; Affordability; Other Health: Health-seeking behavior; Accessibility; Discrimination; Affordability; Other Stigma discrimination: Law and policy; Enforcement/judiciary; Service delivery; Discrimination in healthcare, community and occupational settings; Other Household burden: Care for the sick; Heading the household (additional economic burden); Disproportionate household-labour; Other The findings from the online survey and the e-discussion are summarized below1. Economic Most participants identified loss of (or inability to find) employment (80%) and the loss of (or inability to generate) income (76%) as the most critical economic impacts of HIV on women and girls in Asia and the Pacific. A relatively smaller proportion of participants also identified drops in ownership and control over economic assets (property, livestock, etc.); increased indebtedness; and diminished access to sources of credit as critical economic impacts (44%, 42% and 34%, respectively). 1 The online survey ran from 15 to 31 July, 2011. A total of 41 responses were collected from respond- ents situated in 18 different countries. The breakdown of respondents by gender was as follows: 63.4% female; 34.1% male; and 2.4% other (specified as transgender). Please see link to the auto generated report of the survey for more information http://appv3.sgizmo.com/reportsview/?key=136951- 769248-9c82f07a894bf442db6b58470783aef3. \u201c Mitigating the impact of HIV on women requires changing many things, and when many things need change, how does one go about such an effort?", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "1ac8e7d3-c747-4524-a134-f3b0d34ac0bf": {"__data__": {"id_": "1ac8e7d3-c747-4524-a134-f3b0d34ac0bf", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-e-discussion-socio-economic-impact-hiv-women-and-girls", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV-APCoP Summary of E-discussion on the Socio-economic Impact of HIV on Women and Girls", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-e-discussion-socio-economic-impact-hiv-women-and-girls", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "774a80cee2c40831ef320a8c3d23d2172f273a40d6a305480992094774f9d33d"}, "2": {"node_id": "e771b0fd-bc85-44cb-8d19-c3b2eb208ebf", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-e-discussion-socio-economic-impact-hiv-women-and-girls", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "d61271d0037f129559df754c9f86b01c899b71309e46fdbf949a8cae982944f0"}}, "hash": "fc8b2c90cfdc98b5be97fb25234ef82a9662428415997773662c2218f449b7e1", "text": "SIlja annIIna RajandeR, CaMbodIan CoMMunIty of WoMen lIVIng WItH HIV/aIdS The Socio-economic Impact of HIV on Women and Girls 5 Participants suggested that the economic impacts of HIV on women and girls in Asia and the Pacific are exacerbated by traditional roles of women which do not monetize their economic contribution to household-owned businesses/ agricultural enterprises. Legislative frameworks that continue to constrain women\u2019s rights to own economic assets (for example, the inability to open bank accounts without husbands\u2019 authorization in Indonesia) contribute to increasing vulnerability of women to the economic impacts of HIV. Food & Nutrition A large majority of participants identified the reduced affordability of food as the most critical food and nutrition-related impact of HIV on women and girls in Asia and the Pacific (76%). Sixty six percent and fifty six percent of participants also identified inadequate nutritional value (quality) of food and the diminished accessibility to food sources, respectively, as the most critical impacts. Participants pointed out how (food) accessibility and (food) quality-related impacts on women and girls are amplified by gender stereotypes within Asia and the Pacific, which skew the effort-reward balance in terms of food provision and allocation. While women expend considerably", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "7b217588-e115-4b78-8c69-a6471b6ca8b8": {"__data__": {"id_": "7b217588-e115-4b78-8c69-a6471b6ca8b8", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-e-discussion-socio-economic-impact-hiv-women-and-girls", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV-APCoP Summary of E-discussion on the Socio-economic Impact of HIV on Women and Girls", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-e-discussion-socio-economic-impact-hiv-women-and-girls", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "a6dbb168730864aadd0ff548a2c5aa93771118a1fcc4eb52c2b300db89dd45c5"}, "3": {"node_id": "5b32a879-e7f0-4622-b50a-fa8aa62435c3", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-e-discussion-socio-economic-impact-hiv-women-and-girls", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "31efb8d7197cccde32ad200c8e215b1bfe1aba2916d3bae49318ac633507b560"}}, "hash": "e997e91fb5664092f52fbb285dcd2523df5874ca022397835b03952e283d7d34", "text": "greater efforts on providing (especially garden crops) and preparing food, since this labour is not wage- remunerated, their access to the most nutritional food is compromised within the household. Education Majority of participants (73%) identified the drop in school attendance (and relatedly, the increase in absenteeism) as the most critical education-related impact of HIV on women and girls in Asia and the Pacific. 71% of participants also considered the reduced ability to afford education as the most critical impact, while 56% suggested a lack of access to formal education is the most critical impact. Participants also noted that in the case of countries that provide free or heavily subsidized education, the quality of education is a key concern. In addition, it was also highlighted that, in many instances, where education is both accessible and affordable, increased household and care burden on girls in HIV-affected households compromises their ability to reinforce what is learned in school through homework. www.hivapcop.org 6 Health A large majority of respondents identified drops in levels of healthcare seeking and the (in)affordability of healthcare as the most critical health related impacts of HIV on women and girls in Asia and the Pacific (71% and 76%, respectively). A slightly smaller majority identified increased discrimination in healthcare settings (66%) and reduced accessibility to treatment and care facilities (63%) as the most critical health-related impacts. Participants noted the interconnectedness of these critical impacts and highlighted how they can operate to reinforce each other and, consequently, encroach on women and girls\u2019 rights to lead healthy, functional lives. For example, discrimination in healthcare settings (and the threat of physical/non-physical violence in social settings) contributes to disincentivising treatment-seeking behaviour. Equally, inaccessibility of treatment and care facilities increases costs of seeking healthcare and, consequently, contributes towards making treatment and care unaffordable. Stigma & Discrimination A large majority of respondents identified increased discrimination in healthcare, community and occupational settings as the most critical stigma and discrimination-related impact of HIV on women and girls in Asia and the Pacific (78%). A relatively smaller majority identified increased discrimination in service delivery (68%); increased discrimination by law enforcement and judicial agencies (68%); and increased discrimination within legislative and policy- making frameworks (61%) as the critical impacts. Participants stressed the need to acknowledge that families are often key sites where women and girls experience discrimination, while calling for greater redress (through legislative reform and more proactive enforcement) for women in instances of sexual assault, domestic violence and other forms of gender- based violence. Household Burden A large majority of participants identified increased care-giving burden (83%); increased economic burden (especially as heads of households) (83%); and an increase in household labour (81%) as the most critical household burden related impacts of HIV on women and girls in Asia and the Pacific. Participants suggested that social protection schemes and strategies might be the most effective way of mitigating the disproportionate increase in household burden experienced by women and girls living with/affected by HIV. \u201c the economic impacts vary considerably between different countries, and depend on national expectations and legislation surrounding women\u2019s ability/right to economic performance. there are some very practical changes that need to take place which overtly discriminate against women\u2019s entry into the business and financial arenas whether at local or larger scale levels. In Indonesia, for example, married women need their husband\u2019s authorisation to open a bank account. Such practices are reinforced by national processes, e.g. the national census assumes that a male is the \u2018head\u2019 of a household and the main income earner. anonyMouS (SuRVey ContRIbutIon) The Socio-economic Impact of HIV on Women and Girls 7 General Observations from the E-discussion Mitigating the Socio-Economic Impacts of HIV on Women and Girls - HIV-Sensitive Social Protection While participants identified several distinct but mutually reinforcing pillars of effective social protection strategies, there was a consensus that social protection is a framework for putting in place comprehensive policies and programmes to protect poor and marginalized individuals and groups from socio-economic shocks. In its broadest sense, microcredit, social transfers, health insurance and protection, transformative legislative laws and regulation are all considered part of social protection. Participants, including women living with HIV, confirmed that HIV-sensitive social protection can significantly contribute towards achievement of all three aspects of the universal access outcomes \u2013 impact mitigation, treatment and prevention.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "5b32a879-e7f0-4622-b50a-fa8aa62435c3": {"__data__": {"id_": "5b32a879-e7f0-4622-b50a-fa8aa62435c3", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-e-discussion-socio-economic-impact-hiv-women-and-girls", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV-APCoP Summary of E-discussion on the Socio-economic Impact of HIV on Women and Girls", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-e-discussion-socio-economic-impact-hiv-women-and-girls", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "a6dbb168730864aadd0ff548a2c5aa93771118a1fcc4eb52c2b300db89dd45c5"}, "2": {"node_id": "7b217588-e115-4b78-8c69-a6471b6ca8b8", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-e-discussion-socio-economic-impact-hiv-women-and-girls", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e997e91fb5664092f52fbb285dcd2523df5874ca022397835b03952e283d7d34"}}, "hash": "31efb8d7197cccde32ad200c8e215b1bfe1aba2916d3bae49318ac633507b560", "text": "Economic Key Impacts Participants reported that the economic impact on women and girls living with/affected by HIV was most severely felt with respect to loss or truncation of employment and alternative forms of income generation opportunities; the depletion of capital; and increased indebtedness, often to primary money lenders. It was pointed out that the", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "884c1d1a-f0e4-4830-8370-6fc048735e80": {"__data__": {"id_": "884c1d1a-f0e4-4830-8370-6fc048735e80", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-e-discussion-socio-economic-impact-hiv-women-and-girls", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV-APCoP Summary of E-discussion on the Socio-economic Impact of HIV on Women and Girls", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-e-discussion-socio-economic-impact-hiv-women-and-girls", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "d4a8a8111e8d0605ef5baeb13e11af80441c4b49c5b8546bb9de8a19dcfd828e"}}, "hash": "d4a8a8111e8d0605ef5baeb13e11af80441c4b49c5b8546bb9de8a19dcfd828e", "text": "economic impact on women and girls is exacerbated by factors that include, but are not limited to: (i) unequal gender structures in society (for example, there are gender inequalities in access to education, which translate into segregated labour markets); (ii) institutional barriers to economic equality between genders (for example, legislation that deprive women of economic autonomy by curbing their rights to inherit assets or own capital); (iii) high levels of external stigma and discrimination (participants report that in Cambodia, villagers refrain from buying agricultural produce from HIV positive women); (iv) high levels of internal stigma (which lowers productivity and translates, in a marketised employment environment, into lower incomes); and www.hivapcop.org 8 (v) classical poverty traps (where low incomes, combined with high marginal propensities to consume, lead to low savings and low levels of capital accumulation that could otherwise cushion the impact of socio-economic shocks \u2013 PNG, with an 80% dependence rate on subsistence farming is provided as a case in point). Impact Mitigation Several participants highlight that conditional/unconditional cash transfer programmes, in addition to providing subsidized access to essential goods and services, can be instrumental in alleviating the economic impact of HIV on households in general, and women and girls, in particular. It was argued that, \u201cThe most obvious benefit of cash transfers for HIV outcomes is in the area of providing care and support; that is helping vulnerable households and individuals to withstand the economic impacts of AIDS. Since care and support for people living with HIV and HIV-affected households is disproportionately the responsibility of women and girls (often elderly women and/or young girls), this alone has a positive impact for women and girls. It is also very important because it can protect the already poor households from slipping further into destitution that can result from HIV related health expenditure as well as from stigma and discrimination. HIV related stigma and discrimination affects people living with HIV and poor HIV-affected households by loss of jobs, lack of access to prevention and treatment services and lack of access to poverty reduction and other impact mitigation programmes\u201d. Participants also provided successful instances of countries where such programmes are already in place, either in to or have been adapted to bring women and girls living with/affected by HIV under their ambit. A government widow pension scheme in Rajasthan, India, which was reformed to cover women \u2013 regardless of their age \u2013 whose husbands died of HIV, was identified as having benefited more than 20,000 women. Similarly, in the Philippines (where the large scale of female migration for employment overseas, accentuates the loss of employment/income generation opportunity following a positive diagnosis) conditional cash transfer programmes (to support, nutrition, healthcare and children\u2019s education) are the cornerstones of the country\u2019s social protection architecture. In Sri Lanka, however, while there is a monthly stipend available to households with disabled members in the family, the provision does not cover households headed by positive women. \u201c ownership of business or farms is another place where women have very little control. Many women in households give all they have to the family business/farm and make a substantial contribution towards it yet they do not have any legal authority and this can be crippling. anonyMouS (SuRVey ContRIbutIon) The Socio-economic Impact of HIV on Women and Girls 9 Food & Nutrition Key Impacts There was consensus among participants that guaranteeing nutrition and food security is fundamental to reducing HIV\u2019s impact on households and especially on women. It was pointed out that women living with/affected by HIV can be affected by food and nutritional issues in two separate ways. Firstly, diminution in household income combined with an increase in care-giving responsibilities for women with family members with HIV contribute to reducing the time spent in food preparation, as well as the nutritional value in the food consumed by HIV- affected households. Secondly, participants also noted, that in several countries in the Asia and Pacific, gender inequalities in the preparation and allocation of food within the household continued to be rigidly followed. Males and boys are served their meals before women and girls eat; this, more often than not, results in an unequal allocation of, if not food, then nutrition. Impact Mitigation Participants also shared their knowledge of food support initiatives in some countries. In the Philippines, the 4Ps (Pantawid Pamilyang Philipino Program) conditional cash transfer programme allocates a certain amount of cash (Php 6,000 annually) to poor households to supplement their nutrition intake. In India, recent legislative reforms in various states have made provisions for PLHIV to have subsidized access to food, nutritional supplements and other essential commodities. In addition,", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "e166ac58-0572-4198-a363-25da76dda4e6": {"__data__": {"id_": "e166ac58-0572-4198-a363-25da76dda4e6", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-e-discussion-socio-economic-impact-hiv-women-and-girls", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV-APCoP Summary of E-discussion on the Socio-economic Impact of HIV on Women and Girls", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-e-discussion-socio-economic-impact-hiv-women-and-girls", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "524819a428a2156e2809b0a1918fadde601053989e4e78746712ecf23a10a201"}, "3": {"node_id": "4dfcca7c-86d1-4d63-b96e-a873385752f7", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-e-discussion-socio-economic-impact-hiv-women-and-girls", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "38ff6a782ff3e61c0aa5aa79805b3a7d4837b8bb15a44177d77d5cad91d7dbde"}}, "hash": "7ec51551dbd189f39707a497ef0921ba67a210cd67135e772cb2e242a23f522f", "text": "even where nutrition support programmes are in place, several participants highlighted the necessity to ascertain that the programmes meet the specific nutrition needs of women and girls. It was pointed out, for example, that providing food support to households does not imply ensuring a gender equitable access to the support by all members of the household. A pioneering WFP initiative in Zambia, where electronic food vouchers are provided to affected households to be expended at the local shop of their choice was also shared. This mechanism, albeit dependent on the presence of functioning markets, has the twin advantages of allowing households to collect food rations at their convenience and attenuating the stigma attached to food collection. Participants, reflecting sentiments from their ground level interactions with positive networks, seemed to suggest that while governments have made the free provision of ARVs and HIV-related treatment services to PLHIV a key priority, providing nutritional guarantees, specifically, to HIV-affected households has become a marginalized area of concern; as such, nutrition is left to the affected www.hivapcop.org 10 households \u2013 already crippled by HIV-related employment and income loss \u2013 to manage for themselves. It is clear that inadequate attention to nutrition not only compromises the effectiveness and efficacy of unemployment/income loss insurance, but also locals PLHIV and affected women/girls in a vicious cycle while low nutrition feeds back to low productivity and low income and back to low nutrition. Thus, in absence of supplementary nutritional support, the sustainability of employment and income support programmes is compromised. Health Key Impacts Participants agreed that while conspicuous advances had been made in extending free ARV/ART to affected populations, the impact of HIV on household health and, especially, on the health of women and girls living with/affected by HIV remained disproportionately large. Inequalities in existing health support structures were attributed to a combination of coverage, extensiveness, accessibility, affordability and quality-related issues in publicly provided (sexual and reproductive) health services). Several participants, across countries, reported a rural-urban divide in women\u2019s access to health (sexual, reproductive and HIV-related) services. A lack of decentralization in medical care provision artificially inflates cost of treatment, as does the lack of financial support for PLHIV to deal with opportunistic infections. These costs can comprise a disproportionately large component of household expenditures for affected households, especially those struggling with employment/income loss. Further, it also compromises women\u2019s access to healthcare, as their lack of control over household finances makes them dependent on male heads of household, who often \u2013 following tradition, especially in rural communities \u2013 deprioritise sexual and reproductive health concerns. Participants also identified stigma (both general social stigma and institutionalized discrimination within the health sector) as a key impediment to women\u2019s (especially those living with/affected by HIV) access to health services. While the potential for being stigmatized in society can disincentivise access to health services due to a fear of disclosure of positive status, institutional discrimination in health care settings can impose significant physical and psycho-social burdens on women in need of care. Impact Mitigation Philippines was singled out as a country having made significant strides in reducing the burden of HIV-related healthcare costs, as well as mitigating \u201c We know that social protection programmes only are not sufficient but need to be coupled with sound macroeconomic policy, good governance and access to basic education and health care for all so that it helps to sustain the already achieved economic gains and further contribute to human development in Papua new guinea. CaRol floRe- SMeReCznIak, dePuty ReSIdent RePReSentatIVe, and PeteRSon Magoola, undP Png The Socio-economic Impact of HIV on Women and Girls 11 problems with the rural-urban differentials in health care accessibility. In an attempt to increase HIV-related treatment coverage by lowering treatment costs, the country has implemented a publicly funded reimbursement scheme for both outpatient and inpatient HIV-related treatment and care. In addition, to minimize rural-urban disparities in access to healthcare, the Department of Social Welfare and Development, with active support from UNDP, has established a \u201creferral system for care and support services of PLHIVs and their affected families and the development of its programme manual. The referral system provides the mechanism, strategies and tools to ensure and enhance the access of PLHIV and their families to a quality and timely delivery of psychosocial, economic and support services.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "4dfcca7c-86d1-4d63-b96e-a873385752f7": {"__data__": {"id_": "4dfcca7c-86d1-4d63-b96e-a873385752f7", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-e-discussion-socio-economic-impact-hiv-women-and-girls", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV-APCoP Summary of E-discussion on the Socio-economic Impact of HIV on Women and Girls", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-e-discussion-socio-economic-impact-hiv-women-and-girls", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "524819a428a2156e2809b0a1918fadde601053989e4e78746712ecf23a10a201"}, "2": {"node_id": "e166ac58-0572-4198-a363-25da76dda4e6", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-e-discussion-socio-economic-impact-hiv-women-and-girls", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "7ec51551dbd189f39707a497ef0921ba67a210cd67135e772cb2e242a23f522f"}}, "hash": "38ff6a782ff3e61c0aa5aa79805b3a7d4837b8bb15a44177d77d5cad91d7dbde", "text": "It is intended to facilitate the convergence of various service providers from multi-sectoral agencies to respond to the emerging needs of PLHIV and their families. To date, over 120 social workers, health care providers, PLHIV and their families were trained for the roll out and operationalization of the system. Moreover, more than 100 social workers", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "acbfc18e-14ca-4536-800c-7010bdd4758a": {"__data__": {"id_": "acbfc18e-14ca-4536-800c-7010bdd4758a", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-e-discussion-socio-economic-impact-hiv-women-and-girls", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV-APCoP Summary of E-discussion on the Socio-economic Impact of HIV on Women and Girls", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-e-discussion-socio-economic-impact-hiv-women-and-girls", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "4281218ed8d584c053157d1a1eada084486632130470715e7f69ca22a031f1d8"}, "3": {"node_id": "492d23ec-5ff3-4466-98ef-71b003040ed8", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-e-discussion-socio-economic-impact-hiv-women-and-girls", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "6b14bf6c41fbec393ee3c14a90da97fbf97a9a4df4d406329d69615af0023018"}}, "hash": "ea1c90781047a2c2ecbc9855b2da095ca1c6a8f663c19a284e24d30d030994a4", "text": "from the sub-national and local offices were trained on providing care and support services to people infected and affected with HIV.\u201d Stigma & Discrimination Key Impacts In previous sections of this summary, participants\u2019 observations about the role of stigma in reducing incentives for women\u2019s access of social protection services (income support, food support and healthcare support) has been documented. Accordingly, this section consolidates the discussions about the positive impact of social protection in reducing the psycho-social impact \u2013 manifested as internal stigma \u2013 of HIV/AIDS on people living with or affected by it. Impact Mitigation As noted earlier, participants suggested that the lack of employment or income not only has a negative impact on the economic circumstances of WLHIV, but also contributes to an erosion in their sense of self worth arising out of a palpable sense of loss of agency. Further, in middle and low income societies, capacity constraints imply that psycho-social support for WLHIV to enable them to cope with this discrimination in self-worth is scarce. In addition, it was highlighted that the problem is exacerbated by the erosion of family networks in erstwhile traditional societies (i.e., by the gradual supplanting of \u2018families\u2019 by \u2018households\u2019). As such, social support systems, especially in the economic domain, have the dual purpose of enhancing economic well-being and enabling WLHIV to maintain their rights to functionally fulfilling and dignified lives. www.hivapcop.org 12 Other Concerns and Issues Raised by Contributors Ensuring sustainability, reachability, ability to target and ability to circumvent capacity constraints in middle and low income countries, was repeatedly highlighted. One participant pointed out \u2013 based on local experiences with social support schemes in Cambodia \u2013 that rapid interventionist models of social protection are not effective as they are not sustainable, extensive in their coverage or adequately cognizant of the local environment. Another general aspect of the discussion on social protection centered around monitoring mechanisms in place to access, review and revisit existing social protection strategies and schemes. There was a clear consensus for the need to develop harmonized indicators that lend themselves to comparative analysis, while measuring and monitoring the effectiveness of current social support interventions against uniform and consistent benchmarks. However, participants noted that such indicators might fail to capture broader, long term goals of particular social protection programmes, as well as the complexity of socio-economic realities lived out at the grassroots level. As such, there is a need to supplement the development of indicators with the practice of sharing best practices from work on the ground. The e-discussion also highlighted the need to incorporate existing community and family structures, as well as networks, to improve the design and diversity of targeted social support. Participants pointed out that this will enable social protection schemes to harness the local knowledge (that is inherent in communities and networks), and empower communities and families to be resilient to socio-economic shocks. An example of this form of partnership is found in Fiji. Here, UNDP, through its Fiji National AIDS Spending Assessment Project, added a component whereby financial assistance was provided to a civil society organization (FJN+), whose members included people living with HIV/AIDS, to develop an advocacy communication and implementation strategy. However, while this approach is promising in general, its applicability to HIV-related social protection is relatively more limited. Unless attitudinal change that challenges socially entrenched gender inequalities and stigma against HIV is first fostered, depending on community/family networks to deliver support, this might exacerbate gender- based inequalities in access to social support. As such, with respect to HIV-based social support, there is still a need to maintain independently and professionally manned referral systems to guarantee unstigmatised access to social protection for women and girls. \u201c one of the most pernicious forms of discrimination is the perpetuation of beliefs and attitudes which reinforce gender stereotypes and gender inequalities of both women and men, particularly in healthcare settings related to sexual and reproductive health. anonyMouS (SuRVey ContRIbutIon) The Socio-economic Impact of HIV on Women and Girls 13 That said, participants were concerned that attitudinal change within family and community (\u201cstrengthening the family core\u201d, for instance) was critical to the sustainability of social protection initiatives. The role of the family as a support system or safety net becomes especially important where markets for social insurance are missing, where market imperfections make privately provided social insurance services unaffordable and where governments fail to provide \u2013 owing to budgetary/capacity constraints \u2013 minimally acceptable levels of social protection.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "492d23ec-5ff3-4466-98ef-71b003040ed8": {"__data__": {"id_": "492d23ec-5ff3-4466-98ef-71b003040ed8", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/h