Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV-APCoP Summary of E-discussion on the Socio-economic Impact of HIV on Women and Girls", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-e-discussion-socio-economic-impact-hiv-women-and-girls", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "14c405477291dfbae34e514c50546698b8209bc6a6ba24d3dfc99928785c536d"}, "3": {"node_id": "5d80d8dd-b998-4871-9ec5-f457fd435d70", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-e-discussion-socio-economic-impact-hiv-women-and-girls", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "571b2034db4b1ed14468a435210e435c66d6f303cabbcc72faca970a259b0b93"}}, "hash": "a99d1d63757df0cefe7f42b0c6a603ecb7000d5745b1884df79a45e9b07ef130", "text": "understood as a unit of economic organization. Accordingly, the household is a competitive environment, characterized by competition for resources and the complex exercise of power. However, the family \u2013 understood as a social unit \u2013 is a collaborative (and not competitive) enterprise sustained by duty and care-based relationships. Participants\u2019 responses suggest that the emphasis on \u2018households\u2019 might explain why women/girls living with/affected by HIV might feel high levels of internal stigma associated with the disruption of their economic functionality, which undermines their resilience. The emphasis on \u2018families\u2019, as networks of relations, on the other hand, builds resilience to socio-economic and HIV-related shocks. The \u201cwantok\u201d system in Papua New Guinea is an example of such a family-based social safety net mechanism. www.hivapcop.org 14 Key Policy Recommendations Taking into account the various elements of socio-economic impact of HIV on women and girls, as well as the gaps in existing mitigation policies and programmes, participants submitted the following key recommendations. Ensure \u2013 in the context where social protection schemes are universal \u2013 that HIV-affected populations, especially women and girls, have full and complete access to their entitlements. Design and deliver mitigation programmes that distribute social protection resources equitably to women and girls in HIV-affected households; equally, strategies to build capacity for socio-economic resilience must be cognizant of the gender specific socio-economic impact of HIV on women and girls. Incorporate cash transfer (conditional or otherwise) components within existing and new social protection schemes to mitigate the impact of socio- economic shocks and ensure women and girls affected and impacted by HIV have access to them. Institute legislative reform to ensure gender equality in the ownership of economic assets (e.g. property, inheritance rights) and autonomy over economic decisions (e.g. freedom to open bank accounts without the authorization of husbands). Empower and involve representatives of affected women in the design, delivery and monitoring of relevant interventions to ensure that their real concerns are appropriately reflected and practical solutions developed. Apply a rights-based approach to all interventions, clearly articulating the role of duty bearers and rights holders and facilitating dialogue and collaboration between the two. Design, implement and enforce anti-discrimination (both gender and HIV- status based) laws in institutional settings (workplaces, schools, healthcare settings, etc.) to combat stigma; minimize the threat of HIV-related income/ employment loss; and improve women\u2019s access to social protection, healthcare and psychosocial services. Expand scope of mitigation policies and programmes, from a piecemeal structure, to address the various dimensions of socio-economic impact of HIV (on employment/income, nutrition, healthcare, education and household burden). The Socio-economic Impact of HIV on Women and Girls 15 Incorporate ground level resources (existing community structures, positive networks) to leverage on local knowledge in order to design and deliver better targeted, more accessible socio-economic interventions with high coverage quotients. Build multi-sectoral partnerships to circumvent financial and capacity constraints in the delivery of social protection services. Develop harmonized indicators to monitor, review and audit mitigation schemes on a constant, consistent basis. The full archive of this e-discussion on the socio-economic impact of HIV on women and girls is available online at http://www.hivapcop.org/e-discussion/e-discussion- socioeconomic-impact-hiv-women-and-girls-asia-and-pacific. The Socio-economic Impact of HIV on Women and Girls 17 How can the HIV-APCoP help you? \u2022\ufffd Provide access to important publications, presentations, tools, and other materials. \u2022\ufffd Provide access to emerging and good practices across the region. \u2022\ufffd Provide information on upcoming events related to HIV, gender, and human rights in the region. \u2022\ufffd Provide peer-review for your studies and guidance to resources under development. \u2022\ufffd Link you to professionals working on issues related to HIV, gender, and human rights. \u2022\ufffd Provide technical advice on specific queries. How can you contribute? \u2022\ufffd Share your organizations work on the HIV-APCoP through publications and best practices. \u2022\ufffd Post details of upcoming events relevant to HIV, gender and human rights in the region. \u2022\ufffd Respond to member\u2019s queries and share your expertise. \u2022\ufffd Participate in e-discussions.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_s