egion. The HIV-APCoP can be accessed via www.hivapcop.org", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "3943908f-08b3-445a-8a63-c7501d389a0a": {"__data__": {"id_": "3943908f-08b3-445a-8a63-c7501d389a0a", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-ediscussion-progress-mdg-3-and-6-women-and-girls-living-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV-APCoP Summary of Ediscussion on Progress on MDG 3 and 6 Women and girls living with HIV in Asia and the Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-ediscussion-progress-mdg-3-and-6-women-and-girls-living-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ece79363d42220ea4dacd7303a9418f3bab22626ff10e0f2db39a632a00434bf"}, "3": {"node_id": "88c770a2-b43c-455b-8d5a-7f8b3209c641", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-ediscussion-progress-mdg-3-and-6-women-and-girls-living-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "625c0989b4413014b1ddd7192405a7eeded5975c529171f72870b8e0c3e31524"}}, "hash": "0b1c897605a6b83a5d6cc465b9e13153a341ee4ba29e007a6672016f4979db5e", "text": "a partnership initiative with Asia Paci\ufb01c Community of Practice on HIV/AIDS, Gender and Human Rights www.hivapcop.org Summary of E-discussion; Progress on MDG 3 and 6 Women and girls living with HIV in Asia and the Paci\ufb01c www.hivapcop.org b This publication has been prepared by the UNDP Asia-Pacific Regional Centre on behalf of UNDP, UNAIDS, UNIFEM, OHCHR and APN+. Photos by Reuters Summary of E-discussion; Progress on MDG 3 and 6 Women and girls living with HIV in Asia and the Pacific Introduction In 2010 the UNAIDS Action Framework for Women and Girls Living with HIV tasked the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) to create and support a process by which national-level networks and organizations of women living with HIV could assess their region\u2019s progress on achieving Millennium Development Goal (MDG) 3 (Promote Gender Equality and Empower Women) and MDG 6 (Combat HIV, Malaria, and other diseases). In response to this request, UNDP conducted consultations with women affected by HIV in India, Papua New Guinea (PNG), and the Philippines. A total of 135 HIV-positive women (70 in India, 35 in PNG, and 30 in the Philippines) were consulted over a period of 30 days. The consultations were followed by an e-discussion with members of the Asia Pacific Community of Practice on HIV, Gender, and Human Rights (HIV-APCoP) \u2013 an interactive and dynamic knowledge network jointly established by UNDP, UNAIDS, UN Development Fund for Women (UNIFEM), UN Office of the High Commissioner for Human Rights (UNOHCHR), and APN+ (a network of people living with HIV in the Asia-Pacific region) in response to the challenges faced by the Asia-Pacific countries regarding HIV, gender, and human rights. The discussion \u2013 titled \u201cProgress to MDG 3 and MDG 6: Women and Girls Living with HIV in Asia and Pacific\u201d \u2013 was designed to share the findings of the consultations with HIV-APCoP members. Based on the feedback received from the 135 HIV-positive women, the discussion was divided into three parts: 1. issues of advocacy, stigma, and discrimination; 2. access to health, antiretroviral drugs (ARVs), and harm reduction technologies; and 3. providing a conducive legal environment, particularly vis-\u00e0-vis violence against women. The discussion ran from 11 August 2010 to 3 September 2011. In total, 27 responses were received from 10 countries: Australia, Cambodia, Fiji, India, Nepal, PNG, the Philippines, Sri Lanka, Thailand, and the USA. Contributions were received from civil servants, civil society organizations, UN agencies, and academia. This booklet is a summary of that discussion. 2 www.hivapcop.org www.hivapcop.org 3 Message from the Guest Moderator Dr. Noeleen Heyzer Under-Secretary-General of the United Nations and Executive Secretary of the United Nations Economic and Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific (ESCAP) The numbers of new HIV infections annually in the Asia-Pacific have stabilized, yet HIV infections among women are on the increase. Of all HIV-positive people in the region, the proportion of women living with HIV rose from 19 percent in 2000 to 35 percent in 2008. Similarly, prenatal transmission continues to rise, accounting for 5.1 percent of new infections in the Pacific in 2005. The impact of HIV on women and girls is experienced more severely compared to male counterparts. Structural gender inequalities work to the detriment of women and girls, increasing their vulnerability to both the causes and consequences of HIV. A number of reinforcing factors place women in \u201cdouble jeopardy\u201d regarding their higher infection rates and greater impact of living with HIV. These include: \u2022\ufffd Harmful norms and practices affecting women and girls, including stigma and discrimination \u2022\ufffd Violence against women \u2022\ufffd Barriers in achieving economic security \u2022\ufffd Barriers in receiving education \u2022\ufffd Barriers in access to services and information \u2022\ufffd The great burden of social care carried by women The key to tackling these issues effectively is the translation of global commitments to MDG 3 on Gender Equality and Women\u2019s Empowerment and MDG 6 on HIV, Malaria, and other Diseases into real change for women and girls in Asia and the Pacific.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "88c770a2-b43c-455b-8d5a-7f8b3209c641": {"__data__": {"id_": "88c770a2-b43c-455b-8d5a-7f8b3209c641", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-ediscussion-progress-mdg-3-and-6-women-and-girls-living-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV-APCoP Summary of Ediscussion on Progress on MDG 3 and 6 Women and girls living with HIV in Asia and the Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-ediscussion-progress-mdg-3-and-6-women-and-girls-living-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ece79363d42220ea4dacd7303a9418f3bab22626ff10e0f2db39a632a00434bf"}, "2": {"node_id": "3943908f-08b3-445a-8a63-c7501d389a0a", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-ediscussion-progress-mdg-3-and-6-women-and-girls-living-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "0b1c897605a6b83a5d6cc465b9e13153a341ee4ba29e007a6672016f4979db5e"}}, "hash": "625c0989b4413014b1ddd7192405a7eeded5975c529171f72870b8e0c3e31524", "text": "The UN system is united in its commitment to this goal, and is working with stakeholders across the region to end the gender inequalities that collectively are the primary driver of the HIV epidemic and the associated heavy cost to women. I am delighted to have this opportunity to launch a virtual discussion on these issues and challenges. One critical issue [for discussion is how gender inequalities in the context of HIV can be addressed through progress on MDG 3 and MDG 6 in the Asia- Pacific region. Specific practical issues for consideration include how best to eliminate the barriers to information, facilitate strategic intervention, and enhance access to services;", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "d3591b8b-73ab-4555-a250-cddf1632749b": {"__data__": {"id_": "d3591b8b-73ab-4555-a250-cddf1632749b", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-ediscussion-progress-mdg-3-and-6-women-and-girls-living-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV-APCoP Summary of Ediscussion on Progress on MDG 3 and 6 Women and girls living with HIV in Asia and the Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-ediscussion-progress-mdg-3-and-6-women-and-girls-living-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "982d80b1041c5a8f22b443f1dadc9ac1d2e1a58bf00dff07f3ff5a542fb555b3"}, "3": {"node_id": "924807ed-93ee-4402-9bfd-972cb61f0011", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-ediscussion-progress-mdg-3-and-6-women-and-girls-living-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "b8640a89b70c8880aefb47567a878c3f607213e108c4dcd2449bac13aa815111"}}, "hash": "d4c902d91789a7c6b5d40952775ccce10ff3af8363d33ca68f8f397fe6d0095b", "text": "how to encourage attitudinal change and effective enforcement of existing laws; and how to implement existing commitments that uphold the rights of women and girls living with HIV. I look forward to your contributions, including suggested recommendations and best practices from your areas of work that would enrich the findings of this study and provide all of us with direction and guidance on the way forward. Together we can make a real difference in the prospects of women and girls living with the threat and effects of HIV across our region. Background In examining the situation in India, Papua New Guinea, and the Philippines, a lack of institutionalized mechanisms for the dissemination of comprehensive HIV related knowledge to school-going adolescents and youth was evident in all three countries. Participants in the UNDP consultations testified that though there was an increase in media attention to HIV-related issues, often the portrayal of those issues \u2013 for example, through the choice of images and words \u2013 represented HIV and people living with HIV (PLHIV) in a negative manner. It was also noted that the primary source of information on HIV education for women and adolescents is through peer groups and the media, and therefore often incomplete and incorrect. In terms of testing, participants from India and the Philippines pointed out that test results were often not kept confidential; on the other hand, discussants from PNG suggested that confidentiality was detrimental to their well-being, citing cases where their HIV- positive husbands had infected them by not disclosing their test results. Counselling was reported to be inadequate in all three countries, and was attributed to uninformed health care personnel and sparsely equipped health care facilities. Especially in India, but also to a large extent in rural Philippines and PNG, participants reported widespread misinformation on prevention of parent-to-child transmission (PPTCT) and prevention of mother-to-child transmission (PMTCT) among health care personnel. In addition, all three countries were found to be lagging in improving women\u2019s access to prevention and harm reduction technologies. Participants reported that female contraceptives were expensive and not widely available, making them dependent on their partner\u2019s usage of condoms. Accordingly, condom usage continues to remain low as a result of social mores, the reluctance of men to use condoms; and, as the Indian participants highlighted, women\u2019s dependence on men to use condoms. More positively, ARV coverage among the participants was comprehensive. However, most women identified logistical bottlenecks in ARV delivery (including remoteness from ART centers, costs of transportation, etc). In a majority of instances, despite ARV being more readily available free of charge, costs remained high as a result of expenses incurred on account of CD4 diagnostic tests, medication for opportunistic infections, and a lack of subsidized access to nutritional supplements. 4 www.hivapcop.org www.hivapcop.org 5 On the issue of discrimination, participants from India reported that there is widespread discrimination across all aspects of social life, including health care, employment, and participation in family and community life. Echoes of similar stigmatization, though to a lesser extent, in the Philippines and PNG point to scenarios where women are denied access to basic medical and surgical care, jobs, and family and social support, and where they are discriminated against by law enforcement agencies based on their HIV status. Further, participants from both India and PNG remarked that female sex workers were systematically ill treated and abused by the police. Violence against women is another common theme that emerges from the discussions in the three countries. A large majority of the women reported having encountered, or knowing others who had encountered, forms of violence (including physical and psychological harassment and abuse) frequently and systematically. Participants revealed that violence was likely to come from within the family and, often, with a male as the perpetrator. Victims of violence rarely report such episodes and attribute their silence to the fact that law enforcement agencies are slow to take action and are most often ineffective. Violations of women\u2019s sexual and reproductive rights, which occur routinely, similarly go undocumented.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "924807ed-93ee-4402-9bfd-972cb61f0011": {"__data__": {"id_": "924807ed-93ee-4402-9bfd-972cb61f0011", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-ediscussion-progress-mdg-3-and-6-women-and-girls-living-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV-APCoP Summary of Ediscussion on Progress on MDG 3 and 6 Women and girls living with HIV in Asia and the Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-ediscussion-progress-mdg-3-and-6-women-and-girls-living-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "982d80b1041c5a8f22b443f1dadc9ac1d2e1a58bf00dff07f3ff5a542fb555b3"}, "2": {"node_id": "d3591b8b-73ab-4555-a250-cddf1632749b", "n