nd girls living with HIV in Asia and the Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-ediscussion-progress-mdg-3-and-6-women-and-girls-living-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c33e0544112f92bf36081526d1c650f1f41345a1c3d2a3abf70e5c13c94ef4b3"}, "3": {"node_id": "c519591f-115a-4723-9d4f-ace0d4545d4e", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-ediscussion-progress-mdg-3-and-6-women-and-girls-living-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "2a895caf20d131be2a631b830871c362648e3dbbce6a3314089a59a78d3e416f"}}, "hash": "2c32eb0bf4c085179251da21a3b3be968c653a28122a33b2272eaf7480b5e071", "text": "Fried, Mandeep Dhaliwal, Deena Patel, Julia Kim, Brianna Harrison, and Brian Lutz, HIV/AIDS Practice, UNDP Jane Wilson, UNAIDS, Regional Support Team, Bangkok 6 www.hivapcop.org www.hivapcop.org 7 Part 1: Advocacy, Stigma and Discrimination a) What can we do to encourage changes in attitudes and practices that will lead to the treatment of HIV-positive women as equal participants in social life? b) How can we formulate and deliver correct, yet culturally appropriate, information to women and girls? Participants in the discussion reiterated that a life free from stigma and discrimination is the cornerstone of human dignity. It was pointed out that while stigma can manifest itself visibly \u2013 through verbal, physical, or other forms of abuse, or through the denial of employment opportunities \u2013 it can also be internalized, contributing to lower self- esteem and impeding the capacity of affected women to lead normal lives. Contributors also concurred that HIV-positive women experience stigma (and corresponding discrimination) in a wide range of social interactions \u2013 within the family and community, in the workplace, and even in health care settings. It was further agreed that sustainable measures against discrimination toward women living with/affected by HIV need to be underpinned by a rights-based approach, as well as be characterized by an increased participation of HIV-positive women in their implementation. In this context, key initiatives were identified, spanning multiple domains. \u2022\ufffd Collecting\ufffdstigma\ufffdrelated\ufffdinformation: It was suggested that informational gaps in our understanding of stigma (of how it is caused, what it is constituted by, what its consequences are, how extensive it is in particular societies, etc.) be urgently addressed. The Stigma Index Report in Sri Lanka and the UNDP-India study on levels of stigma are examples of such measures that need to be reproduced more widely and frequently. Evidence on the correlation between discrimination and the levels of new infection must be generated. Not only will this allow better policy design but it will also justify the scaling-up of advocacy in favour of people living with HIV. \u2022\ufffd Building\ufffdeconomic\ufffdcapacity\ufffdfor\ufffdwomen\ufffdliving\ufffdwith/affected\ufffdby\ufffdHIV: Participants agreed that economic empowerment of women living with/affected \u201c \u201d The purpose of participation reaches beyond an ethical commitment: women living with and affected by HIV are uniquely placed to assess and analyze their region\u2019s response to gender inequality and AIDS and, indeed, progress towards achieving all of the MDGs. In many cases these are women who have first-hand experience of the impact of gender inequality on HIV vulnerability, and vice versa. While statistical assessments can provide a broad overview of a country\u2019s progress, they cannot fully reveal what that progress (or lack of) means in terms of the lives of women and men in communities. Susana Fried, UNDP by HIV improves their resilience to stigma and discrimination. Expanding the coverage of micro-credit facilities as well as ensuring that women have rights to land and property can play a major role in enabling HIV- positive women to live meaningful and productive lives with dignity. Increased and equal access to economic resources can compensate for reduced opportunities for employment in the formal sector, combat the low self-esteem that results from economic discrimination, and increase the level of respect that HIV-positive women command in the community. UNDP\u2019s initiatives in India, in partnership with local banks, to increase women\u2019s access to micro-finance, as well as its efforts, in partnerships with UNAIDS, UNIFEM and IAJW, to enhance the inheritance and property rights of women living with HIV in Nepal, have been acknowledged as model initiatives. \u2022\ufffd Building\ufffdsocial\ufffdcapacity\ufffdfor\ufffdwomen\ufffdliving\ufffdwith/affect\ufffdby\ufffdHIV:\ufffd Participants identified an urgent need for equipping HIV-positive women with requisite social skills and support networks to boost their resilience against stigma and discrimination. It was argued that building the leadership potential of these women would empower them to advocate directly on matters that concern their well-being. Relatedly, community structures, such as self-help groups and strong HIV-positive networks, can contribute to helping these women assimilate more seamlessly into society as well as provide them with stronger leverage in lobbying for the rights.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "c519591f-115a-4723-9d4f-ace0d4545d4e": {"__data__": {"id_": "c519591f-115a-4723-9d4f-ace0d4545d4e", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-ediscussion-progress-mdg-3-and-6-women-and-girls-living-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV-APCoP Summary of Ediscussion on Progress on MDG 3 and 6 Women and girls living with HIV in Asia and the Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-ediscussion-progress-mdg-3-and-6-women-and-girls-living-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c33e0544112f92bf36081526d1c650f1f41345a1c3d2a3abf70e5c13c94ef4b3"}, "2": {"node_id": "b6f49d3c-4302-42b6-a19c-592cf4d07819", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-ediscussion-progress-mdg-3-and-6-women-and-girls-living-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "2c32eb0bf4c085179251da21a3b3be968c653a28122a33b2272eaf7480b5e071"}}, "hash": "2a895caf20d131be2a631b830871c362648e3dbbce6a3314089a59a78d3e416f", "text": "Crucially, this would also pave the way for greater and more meaningful participation of HIV-positive women in the political mainstream in order to precipitate the attitudinal reform necessary to combat HIV-related stigma. In this regard, UNDP\u2019s Leadership Development Programme as well as ACHIEVE\u2019s initiatives in augmenting affected women\u2019s advocacy in the Philippines were highlighted. \u2022\ufffd Sensitization\ufffd initiatives\ufffd involving\ufffd HIV-positive\ufffd women:\ufffd Contributors\ufffd to\ufffd the\ufffd discussion agreed that initiatives to sensitize health care professionals, law enforcement officers, community leaders, and the media about the needs and vulnerabilities of women living with HIV/AIDS needed to be scaled-up. There was also a consensus on the need for the active involvement of HIV-positive women in", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "159a80aa-7a3b-4f16-8d06-ee78ff41e995": {"__data__": {"id_": "159a80aa-7a3b-4f16-8d06-ee78ff41e995", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-ediscussion-progress-mdg-3-and-6-women-and-girls-living-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV-APCoP Summary of Ediscussion on Progress on MDG 3 and 6 Women and girls living with HIV in Asia and the Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-ediscussion-progress-mdg-3-and-6-women-and-girls-living-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "9b81fedc22bddb584e5133da045b1b9d01e74f77e601ca14d00ec7c3cfafdc78"}, "3": {"node_id": "31cf23cd-a482-4a97-9dc3-8248dce831cc", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-ediscussion-progress-mdg-3-and-6-women-and-girls-living-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "5e5ff1e5c22d1a8ebf6cb88ca1a20b8d7929334448b686e4b9de70fc84ab31aa"}}, "hash": "18362461e3878dab1bc219a2bf9f52995c4a9a86d1539ecc77838304b2892dce", "text": "such sensitization campaigns. It is envisaged that such interventions would combat HIV-related stigma at the individual level (by building the capacity of women living with/affected by HIV to function as HIV activists and educators), the social level (by providing correct and relevant information to communities, and thereby normalizing HIV-positive status), and the policy level (by establishing platforms for cross-constituency dialogue and cooperation). Some participants noted the need to engage men and boys in particular in improving community awareness on HIV and PLHIV. Among the resources highlighted during the e-discussion were the 2009 paper by the International Center for Research on Women (ICRW), which has a comprehensive list of recommendations to combat HIV-related stigma in health care settings; ACHIEVE\u2019s initiatives in sensitizing media personnel about responsible HIV-related reporting; and a UNDP-supported initiative to sensitize police officers in Tamil Nadu, India. 8 www.hivapcop.org \u201c \u201c \u201d \u201d If the Stigma Index points to anything, it points to the need for positive living \u2013 how to live positive, productive, and full lives with HIV \u2013 in Sri Lanka. David Bridger, UNAIDS Sri Lanka The HIV vulnerabilities of migrant women and the dual stigma and discrimination faced by HIV positive migrant returnees is a special issue of concern for the Philippines. Malu Marin, ACHIEVE www.hivapcop.org 9 Part 2: Access to ARVs, Prevention and Harm Reduction Technologies a) What has been/can be done to provide gender responsive HIV care and support services that are affordable, keeping in mind that resources \u2013 both physical and human \u2013 are limited, that numerous bottlenecks exist, and that stigma and discrimination surrounding HIV are major obstacles? b) Given these limitation, how can we improve the coverage and quality of PMTCT and PPTCT services? c) How can we improve counselling and testing without compromising confidentiality and the health of spouses and partners? d) What strategic interventions can expand the acceptability and usage of harm reduction technologies and prevention methods by women and girls? Discussions in this section elaborated on the key bottlenecks in expanding the coverage of treatment, prevention, and harm reduction technologies as a way of identifying key areas for intervention. Contributors pointed out that effectiveness of treatment is severely hampered by the lack of comprehensive pre- and post-test counselling. Treatment services are further marred by a lack of appropriately trained personnel; concerns about breaches of confidentiality by health care workers; the potential for discrimination in health care settings; and logistical difficulties in accessing treatment centres. A lack of awareness about the role of ARVs and nutritional supplements in managing HIV was also cited as playing a part in preventing HIV-positive women from using treatment facilities. In Vietnam, for instance, some health care workers are reported to consider treatment as a waste of money on the premise that persons with HIV have no chance of survival. Inadequate financial resources were also identified in the discussions as a key impediment to sustained access to treatment technology. In terms of access to other treatment related services, participants noted that, while CD-4 testing is relatively easily available and affordable, facilities providing viral load testing and drug resistance testing are virtually inaccessible. PPTCT/PMTCT services are under utilized in many countries (Vietnam and Indonesia, for example) because women are unaware of ARV regimes that prevent vertical transmission. Participants in the e-discussion agreed that research on the impediments to universalize access of HIV-positive women to treatment related services is urgently required in several countries in order to generate baseline data (especially in the Pacific) and to gain a holistic understanding of factors that restrict access to prevention, testing, and treatment services for women in various risk categories. Consideration of the initiatives suggested here indicates the substantial degree of crossover between efforts to reduce stigma/discrimination and strategies to increase access to treatment services. \u201c \u201d Provider Initiated Counselling Testing is at times misinterpreted at the ground level by UN staff as mandatory, and people are not given the choice to opt out. In the case of women and girls, once they are confirmed HIV-positive, then the drama starts. How to tell their partners is a real dilemma as it can end up in violence and being thrown out of their homes. I have watched a number of incidents that have happened already here in PNG and I am really concerned.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "31cf23cd-a482-4a97-9dc3-8248dce831cc": {"__data__": {"id_": "31cf23cd-a482-4a97-9dc3-8248dce831cc", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-ediscussion-progress-mdg-3-and-6-women-and-girls-living-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV-APCoP Summary of Ediscussion on Progress on MDG 3 and 6 Women and girls living with HIV in Asia and the Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-ediscussion-progress-mdg-3-and-6-women-and-girls-living-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "9b81fedc22bddb584e5133da045b1b9d01e74f77e601ca14d00ec7c3cfafdc78"}, "2": {"node_id": "159a80aa-7a3b-4f16-8d06-ee78ff41e995", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-ediscussion-progress-mdg-3-and-6-women-and-girls-living-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "18362461e3878dab1bc219a2bf9f52995c4a9a86d1539ecc77838304b2892dce"}}, "hash": "5e5ff1e5c22d1a8ebf6cb88ca1a20b8d7929334448b686e4b9de70fc84ab31aa", "text": "Maura Elaripe, PNG-Australia HIV & AIDS Program 10 www.hivapcop.org \u2022\ufffd Comprehensive and periodic research needs to be conducted across various countries to bolster understanding of factors that inhibit access to health care services and to generate baseline and longitudinal data that could be used for monitoring the efficacy of strategic interventions. This information could", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "bba32f1c-69e5-478c-b07c-a925f4fe3420": {"__data__": {"id_": "bba32f1c-69e5-478c-b07c-a925f4fe3420", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-ediscussion-progress-mdg-3-and-6-women-and-girls-living-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV-APCoP Summary of Ediscussion on Progress on MDG 3 and 6 Women and girls living with HIV in Asia and the Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-ediscussion-progress-mdg-3-and-6-women-and-girls-living-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "cd210815622c8362852c996cc3e8b55b3344f746c05540658e712ca573fd7c7e"}, "3": {"node_id": "127ab2ee-3c4c-4392-9d74-cdb643e46a66", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-ediscussion-progress-mdg-3-and-6-women-and-girls-living-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "0bcffc27eb42a4999da07f6c2831097a53fc5ca9e30ac292157b81f74262675f"}}, "hash": "87bbde093649de7cfa1a569b7a74c139d7c860d95e4520c346e76c0f73be72a8", "text": "be further deployed to scale-up advocacy for increased allocation of government funds to augment national treatment capacities by enhancing physical and human infrastructure. The 2009 APN+ study and the proposed study by ICRW in India provide good models \u2022\ufffd Treatment related awareness, especially in terms of reducing vertical transmission among HIV-positive women, needs to be boosted. This could be achieved by deploying such women as peer educators; by building strong HIV-positive networks; and by promoting participation in these networks as an effective way of disseminating accurate and relevant information. \u2022\ufffd Economic empowerment of HIV-positive women is imperative to augment their control over financial resources. Sustainable incomes are indispensable for sustained access to diagnostic, treatment, and supplementary care services. Again, in this context the expansion of micro-finance services and the guaranteeing of women\u2019s property and inheritance rights play a vital role. \u2022\ufffd Elimination of community-level stigma and discrimination in health care settings was acknowledged as an important way to enhance the utilization of treatment services by women. In many instances this can lower the costs of access to services by enabling women to use more geographically proximate treatment and counselling facilities. \u201c \u201d I personally think that our attempts to addressing this issue is very much focus on the victim. It is like we are reacting to an action rather than preventing it from happening in the first place. A women who lives with daily violence is so controlled that she loses her physical strength to give voice to the issue. She in most part believes that it must be her fault and that she asked for it through her actions. Annie McPerhson, Igat Hope www.hivapcop.org 11 Part 3: Gender Based Violence a) What can be done to precipitate more effective enforcement of existing laws against gender-based violence? b) What other structural interventions in addition to legislation and law enforcement can curb gender-based violence?? c) What can be done to foster the social transformation necessary to end gender- based violence and to build women\u2019s resilience to violent behaviour originating either within the family or from outside? Participants suggested that a useful and insightful way of understanding the roots of gender-based violence (GBV) was by contextualizing it as an instrument that perpetuates the hegemony of the male in a patriarchal social order. It was suggested that this theoretical understanding enables an appreciation of the basis of violence and, accordingly, must inform any intervention targeted to eliminate or minimizes the incidence of the same. In response to the call for suggestions to bolster the enforcement of existing laws against GBV, it was pointed out that lawmakers and enforcers, overwhelmingly male, have little incentive to enforce laws that threaten their own privileged position within families and communities. In addition, with particular reference to PNG, the normalization of the notion of GBV \u2013 and domestic violence, in general - pushes acts of violence into the private domain. This not only silences victims of violence but also prevents concerted efforts by law enforcement agencies to act against any abuse that is reported. Another key social characteristic that sustains GBV is the economic and social dependence of women on men. As one participant put it, the woman \u201cmust not provoke the man\u201d for fear of the threat to her \u201csecurity, shelter, family\u2019s comfort, love, food, and even her life\u201d. The discussion recommended remedial steps, the major aspects of which are listed below. Nonetheless, they share an emphasis on involving men in the attempts to foster change, on the empowerment of women to sever their dependence on men, on strengthening the legal infrastructure to redress women\u2019s grievances, and on improving the enforcement of laws by sensitizing law enforcement officers through a bottom-up approach that involves communities leaders as well. Specifically, key recommendations include the following: \u2022\ufffd Provision of legal aid to women who are victims of violence plays an important role in establishing a credible deterrent to GBV. UNDP\u2019s initiatives in Cambodia to ensure women\u2019s access to grievance redressing mechanisms and the UNDP-supported establishment of Legal Aid clinics in India were highlighted as pioneering efforts. So, too, was a UNDP initiative in Nepal designed to improve awareness among women of remedies available to combat GBV and how best to make use of them.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "127ab2ee-3c4c-4392-9d74-cdb643e46a66": {"__data__": {"id_": "127ab2ee-3c4c-4392-9d74-cdb643e46a66", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-ediscussion-progress-mdg-3-and-6-women-and-girls-living-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV-APCoP Summary of Ediscussion on Progress on MDG 3 and 6 Women and girls living with HIV in Asia and the Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-ediscussion-progress-mdg-3-and-6-women-and-girls-living-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "cd210815622c8362852c996cc3e8b55b3344f746c05540658e712ca573fd7c7e"}, "2": {"node_id": "bba32f1c-69e5-478c-b07c-a925f4fe3420", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-ediscussion-progress-mdg-3-and-6-women-and-girls-living-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "87bbde093649de7cfa1a569b7a74c139d7c860d95e4520c346e76c0f73be72a8"}}, "hash": "0bcffc27eb42a4999da07f6c2831097a53fc5ca9e30ac292157b81f74262675f", "text": "\u201c \u201d It\u2019s culturally acceptable in Papua New Guinea for men to use force against women in most circumstances, and so we don\u2019t quickly respond to a woman\u2019s plea in a violent situation where a husband or boyfriend is involved. It becomes an ordinary/normal wife- husband affair, and everyone thinks it\u2019s just two people who are not on good terms with each other.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "e456d5a4-4380-49e3-9d3b-4ded1b82e599": {"__data__": {"id_": "e456d5a4-4380-49e3-9d3b-4ded1b82e599", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-ediscussion-progress-mdg-3-and-6-women-and-girls-living-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV-APCoP Summary of Ediscussion on Progress on MDG 3 and 6 Women and girls living with HIV in Asia and the Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-ediscussion-progress-mdg-3-and-6-women-and-girls-living-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e2738a5c33b149b1e2006587940f142c54e52f45f2ed7307a282be7b4c0f50f4"}, "3": {"node_id": "da34edd5-7384-47a9-a40c-b979ae95afdb", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-ediscussion-progress-mdg-3-and-6-women-and-girls-living-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "8788af685704bcc00514e9f15d349fd8351a6d424b3ebca234dd160da5a01cce"}}, "hash": "2f70383d1083b741f6ec5efeb965a6137a9de122142d9f28add0e6b3bcb703a9", "text": "It\u2019s a private matter \u2013 go home and solve it! Due to this, I think most of PNG mothers in the rural villages are living with pains, sores, and broken limbs and bones. Jacob Kupu, Department of National Planning & Monitoring, PNG 12 www.hivapcop.org \u2022\ufffd Involving communities, and especially men and boys, was identified as indispensable in catalyzing attitudinal change. These efforts, targeting the root causes of GBV, constitute what are termed \u201cprimary prevention strategies.\u201d Such strategies are seen as necessary complements to other strategic interventions, including, for example, the involvement of Village Facilitators in UNDP\u2019s Cambodia Program to conduct community-level conversations on GBV with the primary intention of challenging the normalization of domestic violence as a private family matter. Conversations about GBV provide the critical space, at the level of the community where acts of private violence can be publicly scrutinized and, hopefully, condemned. Participants in the e-discussion asserted that the success of de-normalizing GBV depends crucially on the engagement of men and boys, premising it on the thesis that males are best placed to challenge the ideologies of domination that underlie episodes of violence against women. A joint UNDP, UN Population Fund, UNIFEM, and UN Volunteers initiative, Partners for Prevention (P4P), launched in 2008, was presented as a model for a coordinated, streamlined intervention addressing the roots of GBV. P4P supports research that explores linkages between masculinity and GBV, and is used to design evidence-based responses to violence through the active involvement of men and boys in the local community. \u2022\ufffd Empowerment of women was seen as critical in the effort to lessen and even eliminate the dependencies of women on men. As highlighted in the earlier sections, empowerment is multidimensional; while economic empowerment can be ensured by developing the capacity of women to earn sustainable livelihoods and by enhancing their control over economic resources, social empowerment is constituted by providing women with platforms from which advocacy against GBV can be carried out. A third dimension focuses on ensuring that women have recourse to such support services as refuge centres, crisis hotlines, and counselling. \u2022\ufffd Sensitization of front-line personnel (police officers and medical professionals, for example) was considered to be of major importance in improving enforcement of existing laws related to GBV. One contributor highlighted UNDP\u2019s support for a Baseline Study of the Royal PNG Constabulary, which aims to develop an effective training curriculum based on the institution\u2019s current responses to GBV, as well as the attitudes of its individual members. It was noted that the baseline data would also contribute to monitoring changes in individual attitudes and institutional approaches over subsequent years. \u201c \u201c \u201d \u201d Although researchers in India have investigated and identified many of the sociocultural factors that make women vulnerable to HIV, what is still not adequately understood is a comprehensive understanding of barriers (perceived and actual) to HIV prevention, testing, and treatment services for women and girls in different settings of risk and vulnerability. Priya Nanda, International Center for Research on Women Male-dominated institutions and ideologies of male domination fuel gender-based violence, and it is essential that more men get involved in allying with women to challenge these expressions of male power. A powerful motivation for men to get so involved is that men, too, are targeted by other men\u2019s violence, as one look at the homicide statistics makes clear. Emma Fulu, Partners for Prevention www.hivapcop.org 13 Conclusion As a result of the e-discussion, a clear consensus emerged regarding the linkages between achieving progress on MDG 3 and on MDG 6. Participants acknowledged that gender inequalities and HIV transmission are locked in a vicious cycle, each feeding off the other, and in so doing exacerbating the vulnerabilities of women to HIV and compromising the ability of HIV-positive women to lead fully functional and fulfilling lives. As an indication of how closely the different dimensions of unequal power relations between men and women and HIV-positive living are intertwined, measures suggested by participants to combat HIV-related stigma included not only improved access to prevention, treatment, and harm reduction technologies but the need to eliminate incidences of GBV as well.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "da34edd5-7384-47a9-a40c-b979ae95afdb": {"__data__": {"id_": "da34edd5-7384-47a9-a40c-b979ae95afdb", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-ediscussion-progress-mdg-3-and-6-women-and-girls-living-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV-APCoP Summary of Ediscussion on Progress on MDG 3 and 6 Women and girls living with HIV in Asia and the Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-ediscussion-progress-mdg-3-and-6-women-and-girls-living-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e2738a5c33b149b1e2006587940f142c54e52f45f2ed7307a282be7b4c0f50f4"}, "2": {"node_id": "e456d5a4-4380-49e3-9d3b-4ded1b82e599", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-apcop-summary-ediscussion-progress-mdg-3-and-6-women-and-girls-living-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "2f70383d1083b741f6ec5efeb965a6137a9de122142d9f28add0e6b3bcb703a9"}}, "hash": "8788af685704bcc00514e9f15d349fd8351a6d424b3ebca234dd160da5a01cce", "text": "Contributors proposed boosting research to generate better and more comprehensive data that could be used to foster a better understanding of the root causes of such gender inequalities and, in addition, serve as benchmarks by which the efficacy of interventions would be evaluated. The empowerment of women through the building of sustainable income-generation capacity and by boosting access to social capital was also seen as a way of responding to the major concerns outlined 