 ability to bring about large-scale transformations in social attitudes depends crucially on the degree to which local communities (and in the case of GBV, men and boys) are involved as agents of change. Finally, the e-discussion was invaluable in bringing participants up to date with relevant literature by identifying and outlining recent studies on the subject. As such, the exercise has created the potential for future collaboration between institutions and individuals for related research, expertise sharing, and cooperation in intervention design and delivery. References APN+ (2009). A long walk \u2013 Challenges to women\u2019s access to HIV services in Asia. Women working group of APN+. www.apnplus.org/document/Access.pdf Goldberg, C. (2010). \u201cFamily abuse in India and South Asia: Changing the cycle - Child brides, child mothers, child victims,\u201d Harvard Public Health Review (Spring/Summer ). www.hsph.harvard.edu/news/hphr/spring-2010/spr10childbrides.html Lewis, I. (2008). \u201cReport on Links Between Violence Against Women and the Transmission of HIV in 4 Provinces of PNG,\u201d University of Canberra, Australia, and National HIV/AIDS Support Program, Papua New Guinea; Funded by the National AIDS Council, PNG with the support of the Australian Government. Nauen E. and B. Goldman (2009). \u201cWomen and HIV / AIDS: An Overview,\u201d The Body Health Resource Corporation. www.thebody.com/content/art45915.html United Nations (2009). Millennium development goals: Second national progress summary report for Papua New Guinea. Department of National Planning and Monitoring, Papua New Guinea. UNAIDS (2009). \u201cHIV transmission in intimate partner relationships in Asia.\u201d www.unaids.org/en/KnowledgeCentre/Resources/FeatureStories/ archive/2009/20090811_Intimate_partners.asp UNAIDS (2009). \u201cReport on the global AIDS epidemic.\u201d www.unaids.org/en/KnowledgeCentre/HIVData/EpiUpdate/EpiUpdArchive/2009/ default.asp UN Economic and Social Commission